# Target-typed `new()`

When the type appears on the **left** of an assignment, on a **parameter**, on a **return type**, or on a **field/property**, use **target-typed `new()`** instead of repeating the type on the right.

## Preferred

```csharp
private readonly Dictionary<string, AgentSession> _sessions = new();

public AlertEnvelope BuildEmpty() => new();

return new HealthReport(status, checks: []);

DoWork(new(retries: 3, timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)));
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
private readonly Dictionary<string, AgentSession> _sessions =
    new Dictionary<string, AgentSession>();

return new HealthReport(status, checks: Array.Empty<HealthCheck>());
```

## Scope

- Concrete-type rule still applies: keep the **type on the left** explicit; only the **right side** collapses to `new(...)`.
- Combine with **`CSharp-Terse-04-CollectionExpressions.mdc`** when the right side is a collection literal — prefer `[]` over `new()`.
- Avoid target-typed `new()` when it would obscure which overload is picked, or when the inferred type is genuinely unclear at the call site.
